{
  "analysis": "We have 16 CPU cores and tesseract takes about 0.5-0.8 seconds per frame. With 380 frames at -P 16, it should take about 20-30 seconds, but the previous attempt was too slow possibly due to high memory usage or overhead. Let me try a more efficient approach: extract at 1fps (190 frames), preprocess images (grayscale + threshold), and OCR with high parallelism. Also, the previous xargs approach may have had issues with the bash -c wrapper overhead.",
  "plan": "Extract frames at 1fps into a new directory, preprocess them with convert (grayscale + threshold), and OCR in parallel using xargs -P 16 with direct tesseract calls (no bash wrapper). Then parse the OCR output to extract moves.",
  "commands": [
    {
      "keystrokes": "mkdir -p /app/frames1 && ffmpeg -y -i /app/video.mp4 -vf fps=1 /app/frames1/f%04d.png 2>/dev/null && ls /app/frames1 | wc -l\n",
      "duration": 10.0
    },
    {
      "keystrokes": "cd /app/frames1 && ls *.png | xargs -P 16 -I{} tesseract {} {} 2>/dev/null && echo \"OCR done\" && ls *.txt | wc -l\n",
      "duration": 30.0
    }
  ],
  "task_complete": false
}
